\begin_layout Standard
Encouraging farmers to adopt new technologies is difficult for various reasons.
 One particularly important reason for the slow rate of adoption is related
 to uncertainty about a new product or practice.
 Often the results, for instance in terms of additional yield or cost savings,
 are not clear a-priori.
 Even after the technology has been tried out, it is often difficult to
 isolate the impact of the technology form all other factors that may affect
 outcomes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Decisions are made on the basis of perceptions and expectations.
 There are often informed by agro-input dealers and seed producers that
 want to sell as much as possible, and therefore have an incentive to exaggerate.
 Farmers also learn for peers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a result, farmers may have inflated expectations of the inputs they use.
 For instance, they may assume that inorganic fertilizer leads to lasting
 improvement of the soil.
 Or they may think that the improved seed they bought does not need fertilizer,
 since it is improved and they already paid a substantial sum for it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the end, farmers observe yields that are lower than expected.
 However, as there are many stochastic factors influence production, including
 the weather, it is hard to attribute harvest outcomes to any specific input
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the above, one would expect that farmers that use improved seed would
 use less fertilizer and other inputs than farmers that use landraces.
 However, in observational data, this relationship may be obscured by selection
 bias, whereby farmers that use improved seed differ in many other aspects
 from farmers that do not use improved seed.
 For instance, farmers that use improved seed may be more likely to use
 more fertilizer in general.
\end_layout

