\begin_layout Standard
With the heterogeneity analysis it seems there is now a nice story for the
 learning failure paper:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- for the entire sample, there seems to be a negative effect on quality
 seed adoption and an increase in use of landraces (disadoption), but it
 is not significant because there are also many farmers that do not use
 improved seed to begin with; for them the information is not very relevant.
 Indeed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- if we restrict the sample to adopters, we clearly see that our video scares
 a large share of adopters back into landraces at midline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- for the adopter we do see a positive effect on yield and expectations
 on yield [it’s not really expectations for the coming season but expectations
 that were met in the last season, we asked: Did you harvest as much maize
 from this plot last season as you expected?, so more yield makes it more
 likely that this question is answered with “yes”] at midline.
 It is important to note that there is no increase in production [there
 is a small increase but it’s not significant?], but rather a decrease in
 crop area.
 This is consistent with a story where at least part of the farmers that
 used improved seed and thought if it as miracle seed abandon this and reduce
 maize growing.
 Positive effect on yield at midline also because dis-adoption cannot have
 an effect, yet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
- at endline there is no effect anymore.
 This seems to suggest that our information is like a one time shock and
 farmer move to a new equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At endline, there’s no effect on adoption anymore but the reduced adoption
 at midline has a negative effect on the overall index of the yield etc.
 outcomes for farmers who used to adopt (if we don’t control for baseline)
 but also for the entire sample (if we control for baseline).
\end_layout

